SYMPTOM_TEXT: Within 2 hours of getting vaccinated, I had severe arm pain at the vaccination site. Approximately 6-7 hours after getting vaccinated I began feeling body aches and chills and had trouble sleeping. When I got up the next morning at 8am (~12 hours post vaccination) I had a horrible headache (most painful I've ever had), body aches, and exhaustion. My headache was at a pain level 10 so I took one Excedrin Migraine around 11am and napped for a few hours. The Excedrin helped to slightly lessen the headache for ~8 hours. I ate soup with dumplings for dinner around 7pm on 4/9 and two hours later began feeling extremely nauseous with severe stomach pains. Around 10pm I had a severe case of the chills and a low fever around 99.8 degrees. At 10:45pm I threw up for the first time. My headache came back quite strong and my fever began to spike. My nausea got better for an hour then came back along with the chills and cold sweats. I had severe aches and body pains along with the nausea and fever until throwing up again around 3 or 4am on 4/10. I continued to have a severe headache, body pains, nausea, and a fever of up to 101.8 for the rest of the night into the morning. I was able to sleep around 7am until 12pm on 4/10. On 4/10 I was able to eat some food, but still felt very nauseous and had a bad headache with a fever, although both had decreased slightly. I took advil around 1pm that day to help with the fever and it reduced from 101.8 to 99.5 in the evening. I still had body aches, a headache, and nausea at night on the 10th, although I was able to sleep a little better. When I woke up on the 11th my headache was much better and my stomach was less upset. The body aches and exhaustion were still present on the 11th all day, although a lot less severe than the days prior. I woke up this morning 4/12 feeling much better, with a very mild headache and body aches. The pain at the injection site began to lessen on 4/11 and is minimal today (4/12).
OTHER_MEDS: Medications: Prozac 20mg, Ritalin 2.5mg, Propranolol 60mg (20mg 3x daily) Supplements / Remedies: Bai He Gu Jin Tang, Jia Wei Xiao Yao San, Melatonin

SYMPTOM_TEXT: After 45 minutes after the vaccination, I experienced sporadic shooting pains in my wrists.  I developed a fever at approximately 6pm April 7th.  Took 500 mg Tylenol.  At approximately 1AM April 7th, developed chills.  Throughout the night, I went from hot sweats to chills that shook me so badly I shook the bed.  I became quite nauseated, and vomited once.  My right arm was painful and every joint in my body ached.  I could barely walk from the bed to the bathroom, which is approximately a distance of 25 feet. My arm was swollen and the area of the injection site developed a pimple-like raised spot with a bright red area surrounding it.  The upper portion of the arm that had the injection, was mottled and sore.  The gland under the right arm was extremely painful and swollen (and is still tender to the touch today, April 12th). Chills  subsided at approximately 7am April 8th.I took Tylenol 500mg every 4-6 hours, not exceeding 3000mg in a 24-hour period and drank fluids. The fever (102 degrees F) continued until approximately 3pm that afternoon. The evening of April at approximately 7pm, I had another fever, and took more Tylenol and then went to bed. I also had extreme fatigue beginning about two hours post injection.  April 7th, I slept a good part of the day. Saturday April 10th, I felt like myself, and  the only residual effect is a mildly sore arm and tender gland under the right arm.
OTHER_MEDS: vitamin E Vitamin C Fish oils  NAC 600mg DHEA 5 mg Pregnenolone 20mg Progesterone 100mg Hormone replacement Testosterone and Estrogen NP thyroid 30mg
ALLERGIES: Demerol Molds, dust, pollens Wasp sting

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I had a very bad case of Covid in January 2021 and have not regained my taste or smell.  I was in bed for 2 weeks and had a prolonged fever up to 105 degrees--so high that I had visual and auditory hallucinations.  I had hair loss in the following months and I also continue to be fatigued.    I received the vaccination on 4/6/21 around 11am; a slight headache and face flushing occurred about 30 minutes after shot, but generally felt ok.  Woke up at 4am on 4/7/21 with chills, extreme joint pain, body aches, migraine headache, and a fever of 101.5 degrees.  Took Tylenol around 6am and went back to bed.  The migraine headache, chills, body aches, and extreme joint pain continued.  I was dizzy and extremely fatigued.  Woke up around 9 am and fever was at 102.7 degrees.  Joint pain and headache were almost unbearable at this point and I took a hydrocodone.  Took temperature around 12 pm and it was 103.5 degrees.  Fever continued rising to 104.4 degrees at 2:30 pm.  Took another Tylenol and went to sleep.  The next day, my fever had fallen back down to 102.5 degrees.  I continued with Tylenol to control me fever to around 101 degrees.   My fever persisted for 3 days.  I still have extreme fatigue, joint pain, burning scalp (which will likely mean more hair loss), zero appetite and weight loss, dizziness, blurred vision, etc.  The side effects are exactly how i felt when I got Covid in January.
HISTORY: Degenerative disc disease in lower back

That night, I had severe arm pain. It continued and was lingering. Pain from my shoulder to my injection site and to my shoulders, neck and jaw pain. It was like a heart attack pain - with the racing heart and the pain in my shoulder - it's similar to those kind of symptoms. Every day I had the pain. The neck pain and jaw pain went away about a week prior to my second dose. The arm pain never went away. I called my doctor and he said he still wanted me have second dose. He prescribed me at that visit, Steroids to start taking after the second dose to deal with the pain in my arm. I had the 2nd dose on January 30th. The arm pain from the first dose has never left and has continued. I am still experiencing the pain. After the second dose, I still had  arm pain (although the pain was masked at first because I took Advil for chills, body aches etc after the second dose). But when I stopped taking the Advil, the pain was back in my arm. I took the prescription for Steroids for two or three days but then I quit as I had side effects from them. After that, I started taking Advil and CBD oil on it. I did see online that it would take 6-8 weeks to heal so I have now called my doctor again because it's been longer than that. I want to see the doctor again at this time. It's getting worse - especially at night. It's really painful and I can't sleep at night.

Fever started at 11:30pm 4/6/2021. Fever ~100 degrees F. Had chills and couldn't get warm, then was hot and drenched in sweat. Repeated all throughout the night (Hot/cold). Took 500mg Tylenol at 12am that night. Woke up at 2am with a ~102.4 F fever. Took another Tylenol. Got out of bed around 8am 4/7 drenched in sweat. Felt nauseous and vomited almost right away and couldn't stop for a few minutes. Still had around 102 F so took 2 more Tylenols. Throughout that night and until Friday, I was achy all over my body. Also, lymph node under left arm pit was swollen and was sore along with my left arm. Throughout the day on 4/7, laid in bed trying to get rest and too nauseous to eat anything other than some cereal in the morning and plain noodles later in the day. Took another Tylenol in the afternoon because I was still staying at 102 F fever. Was slightly dizzy when standing up or moving too fast. I slept the next night and felt fine 4/8 morning (no fever), but felt worse as the day went on, aching everywhere and feeling more and more dizzy. Friday 4/9, I woke up in the morning and when I first started walking, I fell on the floor because of extreme dizziness. The whole day I was extremely dizzy and I've never had vertigo before, but it seemed like that based on explanations of it. Also had painful headache every time I stood up, but was fine when I wasn't moving. The next day it was mild dizziness and completely gone the day after that.  Also, Thursday 4/8 around 7:30pm, I noticed I had hives on the back of my right hand. Not 100% sure if it's due to the vaccine, but I'm not sure what else would have caused it and it's worth noting. It was gone the next day.

20yoF with history of functional movement disorder (followed by Dr. (Name) and previously seen by Dr. (Name), movement specialist in our department) now presenting with worsening of baseline myoclonus in the setting of receiving the COVID vaccine earlier on 4/5. On exam, she is alert, in NAD with myoclonic jerks, RUE > LUE, perhaps more prominent than usual for her. She is distractible when engaging in parts of exam, such as while holding her mask or before I enter the room. She did not have any dystonia on exam; she has normal tone. Her neurologic exam is otherwise normal with full strength and symmetric reflexes. Most likely this represents a worsening of existing functional movement disorder i/s/o stressor of receiving the vaccine. Given relative distractibility, absence of dystonia, and lack of response to 50mg of Benadryl, this does not look consistent with a dystonic reaction.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient reported a history of nervousness around needles and had passed out after an immunization in the past. I walked her through the immunization process and after administering her vaccine, I asked her if she was feeling ok before allowing her to leave the clinical room. She stated she was feeling ok so I instructed her to have a seat in the post-vaccination waiting area just outside the pharmacy for 30 minutes so we could observe her as a safety precaution. Shortly after sitting down, the patient fell off her chair. I ran out to check on her and found her unconscious and lying face down on the floor. As soon as I touched her shoulders she began to wake up and tried to get up. I asked her to remain laying down and offered to help her roll over onto her back. I asked her if she could tell me her name - she responded correctly. I asked if she knew  where she was and she correctly stated she was at store. I had her take some deep breaths until her color came back and when she asked if she could please sit up, I assisted her into her chair and asked a technician to get a bottle of water for her. She felt a little shaky so I continued to hold onto her shoulders until she felt completely stable. She was able to take a few sips of water which helped her feel more steady. EMS arrived and checked her blood pressure and blood glucose levels. She was cleared by EMS and chose not to go to the hospital for further care. I had her call a friend to drive her home and stay with her for a while to make sure she was ok.
LAB_DATA: EMTs arrived and checked blood pressure and blood glucose levels

I was mostly fine after that. Before shot #2 I relayed symptoms again to the pharmacist and she said to expect something similar for my second shot. After shot #2 I felt nothing except a sore arm until nine days later when I was hit with extreme dizziness, light-headedness, and nausea while driving. The symptoms persisted for several days and I went to my doctor to see if it could be a reaction to the vaccine. The doctor said no because it was too far out from my shot date and believes it's "motion sickness/vertigo" due to my age/gender and prescribed me Dramamine to get by. I'm still experiencing symptoms 13 days out from the date of my second shot.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Reportedly had some redness and blotchiness at the time but currently no signs of anaphylaxis with no urticaria, no respiratory involvement, no intraoral swelling or voice changes, no GI symptoms. His reported inability to move her arms and legs does not seem consistent with a neurologic etiology of this complaint and more likely consistent with anxiety/conversion reaction in the setting of a vasovagal episode.  Will give zyrtec at mother and patient's request, PO challenge and reassess.
OTHER_MEDS: Acetaminophen, Albuterol MDI, EpiPen, Hydroxyzine, Aygestin
HISTORY: 17-year-old transgender male with history of ADHD, asthma, anaphylaxis, pelvic kidney, depression, self-injurious behavior and eating disorder presents after near syncopal episode approximately 15 minutes after receiving Covid vaccine today.  Complaint of dizziness and tingling in both arms, blotchy rash to face and now complains that he is unable to move his arms and legs.  No true syncope per mother.  No confusion or change in mental status.  No headache.  No chest pain or palpitations.  No shortness of breath or throat tightness or itching.  No hives.  States he cannot feel anything in his body.  Denies any fevers or recent illness.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Odd sensation on tongue shortly after vaccination.  By the next day issues with taste - diminished and foods tasted "off".  The taste issues largely resolved within 7-10 days.  (Some fatigue on days 2-4 after vaccine.) Due to taste issue, had a covid test which was negative.  The sensation on the tongue is always present but sometimes feels like a sore in a particular location, sometimes, feels like the tongue was burned by a hot beverage, and sometimes is just a vague sense of discomfort. Typically on the left side (shot in left arm), sometimes in the middle, rarely on right.  Location is tip of tongue or the top of tongue near tip.   Have seen Family Medicine Doctor who thought taste buds were inflamed. Dentist and ENT have said tongue/mouth look normal on exam. Family Medicine doctor and ENT said to report as possible vaccine side effect, and ENT stated that he believes vaccine is cause.
PRIOR_VAX: reaction to smallpox vaccine as infant.

Thought it was allegic reaction; Experience a lot of tiredness; Experience / a sore / throat / she thought / was an allergic reaction; Experience / itchy throat / she thought / was an allergic reaction; Experience a stiff arm; Headache; First Shingrix dose in Sep-2020 / Second dose / on 6-Apr-2021; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of allergic reaction in a 60-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   The patient's past medical history included shingles (Patient stated that she had shingles 35 years ago.). Previously administered products included Shingrix (1st of dose Shingrix received in September 2021, no problems.).   On 6th April 2021, the patient received the 2nd dose of Shingrix (intramuscular). On 6th April 2021, 12 hrs after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced allergic reaction, tiredness, sore throat, itchy throat, limbs stiffness, headache and drug dose administration interval too long. On an unknown date, the outcome of the allergic reaction and drug dose administration interval too long were unknown and the outcome of the tiredness, sore throat, itchy throat, limbs stiffness and headache were not recovered/not resolved.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the allergic reaction, tiredness, sore throat, itchy throat, limbs stiffness and headache to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were provided as follows: The case was reported by patient. The age at vaccination was not reported. The patient was late for 2nd dose because she was in another state for three months which led to drug dose administration interval too long. In the morning or afternoon time, the patient received 2nd dose in the left deltoid. The patient stated that she was not feeling well and was pretty sick. The patient further described this by describing the symptoms she had. death Narrative:  70 yo male received COVID19 vaccine on 2/16/2021 (first dose) without complications. Patient was admitted to the facility on 3/12/2021 and transferred out to a hospital on 3/15/2021. Patient died on 3/24/2021 due to acute respiratory failure at a medical center. This report is being written because patient received Pfizer covid19 vaccine, Facility requires we report to VAERS if death occurs within 42 days of vaccination. Prior to his hospital admission, his previous one was 5/11/2020-5/14/2020. Please see below for hospital course at the Facility: 70 yo male with PMHx of COPD, CHFrEF 20%, CAD s/p MI and CABG in 1999, HLD, HTN, DM2, GERD, Anxiety and Depression who presented with increased shortness of breath to facility. Transfered on 3/13 to the facility. Noted increased SOB without CP, palpitations, cough, orthopnea or PND. No history of home O2 use but required 2-3L O2 during this hospital stay. Was noted on admit to Facility to have troponin elevation with unchanged EKG. Was started on NSTEMI protocol with heparin ggt, ASA, BB, and statin. Initially received one dose ceftriaxone/azithro for possible PNA. On admission, primary team held home BB. On arrival to Facility, troponin at 3.998 trended to 4.442 and then trended down. underwent CTA to evaluate for PE that was negative. CXR and CT showed pulmonary edema consistent with HF exacerbation and a proBNP 8613. Patient was given 40mg IV lasix x2. RRT was called twice, once for BP 80/50 treated with 500ml IVF, and second for CP that resolved with NTG and tramadol. Cardiology was consulted with goal to cath patient, however some concern for medication adherence going forward so they will reevaluate. Patient began to have tachycardia with rates in the 150s sustained and hypotension. EKG showed likely sinus tachycardia with wide QRS similar to prior EKGs. Patient has ICD in place that was interrogated and showed good function. IV metoprolol 5mg given x3 with rated decrease to upper 120s. Patient remained asymptomatic, awake, and alert. Per discussion with wife after transfer, patient BP has been in the 50s systolic at home for the last month. Cardiac cath was performed showing 99% stenosis of LCX. Did not tolerate procedure with nausea, vomiting, and altered mental status. RRT was called after cath procedure. He is nauseous, diaphoretic. He complained of chest pressure. STAT EKG obtained. Noted ST depressions in the septal leads significant from before. Cardiology concerned pt was having an inferior MI. STEMI call was activated and hospital cath lab was called and report given to the cardiologist on call. Pt was then transported to the Facility and he passed away on 3/24/2021.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Significant elevation of troponin of 12; chest pain; Vaccine induced myocardial injury; headache; myalgia; fever; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable physician. A 28-year-old male patient received second dose of bnt162b2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 MRNA VACCINE, Solution for injection, Lot Number: EN6205), intramuscular, administered in left arm on 24Mar2021 at 1:00 pm as single dose for covid-19 immunization. The patient medical history was not reported. Concomitant medication(s) included keppra, lamictal same dose for more than 5 years. The patient previously took bnt162b2 on 03Mar2021 for covid-19 immunization at the age of 28-year-old at 1:00 pm. Prior to vaccination, the patient was not diagnosed with COVID-19. Since the vaccination, the patient has been tested for COVID-19. The patient stated 1-2 days after vaccine he developed headache, myalgia, fever, chest pain. Chest pain progressively worsened. He was presented to the hospital 3 days after onset. There was significant elevation of troponin of 12, ECG unremarkable. No prior history of hypertension/ hyperlipidemia or diabetes. On 25Mar2021, the patient was diagnosed with vaccine induced myocardial injury. Treatment for events was inpatient monitoring, Heparin infusion while awaiting results of cardiac work up. Outcome of events was recovering.  Follow up attempts are needed and Information on lot/batch number was available.; Sender's Comments: Based on temporal association and profile of the product, the contributory role of the suspect product  bnt162b2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 MRNA VACCINE, Solution for injection, Lot Number: EN6205),  to reported events is possible.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: HPI: Patient is a * year old * who presents following administration of a single dose of J&J COVID19 vaccine in the left deltoid.  Patient states she started to experience ocular burning and tearing about 20 minutes following administration of the vaccine.  She denies ocular pain.  Patient denies wearing contacts, eye makeup, and face products at this time.  She relates that she spent most of her day outside in the sun today but has never experienced these symptoms in the past.  She reports an allergy to amoxicillin and numerous food sensitivities.  She has never required epinephrine for treatment of aforementioned allergies.  She denies a history of seasonal allergies.  She relates that she has a past medical history of PCOS.  She does not take medication on a daily basis.  She denies chest pain, difficulty breathing, swelling of the face/lips/tongue/throat, skin rash/itching, cramping abdominal pain, nausea, and vomiting.     Exam (update as needed): GEN: Alert and oriented x 4, NAD. HEAD: NCAT EYES: Conjunctival injection bilaterally.  Tearing noted in the bilateral eyes.  No purulence noted.  No foreign body noted.  Surrounding tissue nonedematous.  Visual acuity grossly intact.  PERRL, EOMI ENT: Ears normal, Nose normal, OP normal, no evidence of angioedema NECK: Supple, without LAD.  CV: RRR, no m/r/g PULM: Clear to auscultation bilaterally, no accessory muscle use ABD: Soft, no tenderness. SKIN: No rashes, skin warm and dry.  No erythema or edema of the injection site. MSK: FROM, MS 5/5 NEURO: Alert and oriented x 4, CN 2-12 grossly intact, no ataxia, gait steady   Clinical Impression/Field Tx: Possible allergic conjunctivitis, bilateral eyes.  Patient not displaying active signs or symptoms of anaphylaxis, to include facial edema and patient demonstrated ability to control airway.  No foreign body was noted in the orbi to explain symptomst, nor was purulence noted, thus decreasing likelihood of infection origin.  Visual acuity was not compromised at the time of exam.  Conjunctival injection and epiphora, in addition to consistent sun and wind exposure, makes an allergic conjunctivitis more likely.   Instructed patient to consult their PCP or follow up with urgent care regarding the post-vaccination reaction.  Also instructed patient to consult an ophthalmologist if they are able to should the eye symptoms not improve.  Recommended patient utilize visine or other normal saline eye drops for burning sensation relief, in addition to OTC antihistamine medication per package directions..  Patient instructed to go to emergency department should they develop chest pain, difficulty breathing, swelling of the face/lips/mouth/tongue/throat, or cramping abdominal pain with nausea/vomiting, as these are signs of possible anaphylaxis that requires immediate intervention.     Medications administered: None   Disposition:  Home

Patient received dose #2 of Moderna vaccine on April 1, 2021. The patient reported that the shot felt like a bee sting and she had fever and chills for 2-3 days. The patient stated that by "day 3," she had swelling and redness of her right arm which continued to get worse, despite using ice. By 4/7, the patient's arm was 2.5 times larger than the other one, swollen down the entire arm and hand. It was red, splotchy, had lesions, and was painful. The patient went to the ER and was admitted to the hospital. The patient was diagnosed with cellulitis. The providers told the patient the vaccine did not go all the way into the muscle but "ran into the tissue." The patient received IV cefazolin x3 days then switched to cephalexin. She was hospitalized for 3 days. The patient is healing and doing better at the time she reported this adverse event to us.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I counselled the patient prior to giving him the Pfizer Covid19 vaccine.  He received the vaccine at 10:10am.  During the 15 minute observation period, one of my technicians was standing next to him talking to another patient.  She saw some papers slip out of patient's hand and noticed he was unresponsive when she tried to talk to him.  She yelled out for help and I ran out and saw his head rolled back, eyes open, and he sounded like he was snoring.  He never left the chair--just his head rolled back.  We tried to rouse him awake and I had my other technician call 911.  I also called for a store manager.  The patient came to about 15-30 seconds later.  I asked him his name, what day it was, and if he knew where he was.   He answered all questions correctly.  He told me that he's fainted before after vaccines, however he never disclosed this to me prior to the vaccine and had answered "no" under the question if you've ever had a serious reaction to the vaccine.  We gave him some water and a cold paper towel.  The paramedics came and evaluated him.  He declined to go to the hospital and his wife came and picked him up.
LAB_DATA: Paramedics took his blood pressure and blood glucose
PRIOR_VAX: I do not know specifics, but he told me once he recovered that this has happened to him in the past (fainting after a vaccine)

Around 6pm I started having normal mild reactions to the covid vaccine. Around 10pm I lost feeling in both arms and my lower legs, but otherwise was still able to move without pain. At about 10:30, the loss of feeling turned into partial paralysis and extreme pain where feeling had been previously lost. My hands refused to stay in any position except for a clenched fist or fingers completely extended. Moving my arms and lower legs was only able to be done with great difficulty. I was worried that it would spread to my chest, so I got up from where I'd been sitting at a desk and began forcing myself to walk up and down my apartment hallway. I was able to do this though my gait was stuttery and uneven, and my pain was about an 8 out of 10. I was alone in my apartment at the time and my hands weren't working well enough to handle my phone. After about 10 or 15 minutes the nerve pain and paralysis subsided and hasn't come back since, but my leg muscles felt incredibly weak the rest of the night and my partner had to help me to make sure I didn't fall over a couple of times. I didn't end up going to the doctor or seeking treatment because it didn't come back.
OTHER_MEDS: Welbutrin and Paxil, but neither were taken the day of vaccination

Everything was fine at time of shot which was at 11:45. I had no effects, I left clinic  around 12: 30 that afternoon, and went to do a job. I headed home around 4 pm and started to feel warm, but thought it was the sun. Around 5:15 I got the chills, very bad. So bad my jaws were shaking. I tried to use a heating blanket to get warm, but was very miserable. About an hour later I started running a fever that kept going up. My ears started to hurt and the ringing was really bad. By 8:30 my fever had spiked to 102 and I was so nauseous I had a hard time moving around, I almost used the bathroom on myself twice. Started burning up but still unable to move, I went outside to cool down and had a family member take me to the urgent care. They said my arm was swollen from the injection site and that everything was normal and that it was a good thing I was having these experiences because it means the vaccine was working.  Gave me nausea medicine and aspirin and sent me home. I was unable to sleep from all the pain in my body and just laid here in pain starting to get really hot. Woke up around 4 soaking wet where I broke the fever and then continued to have a mild fever all day Sunday, April 11, with mild sweats on and off when my body would get too hot. Today just been trying to move around but very tired and exhausted. Had hard time sitting up to do some work at the table, so been laying down most of the day.
LAB_DATA: No tests were done at the urgent care, I requested an IV of fluids because I know I was dehydrated but they did not want to do anything. No lab work was done, even though I mentioned that I had thalassemia.

ALLERGIES: Gluten Free, no iron, no malarials.

The second and third days after the March 29 dose, I experienced sinus headaches.  I kept the worst of the pain at bay by taking acetaminophen and ibuprofen. On April 5, I began to feel dizzy, nauseated, very tired and had a severe sinus headache.  I also experienced a strong smell of cigarette smoke when no one else could smell it and there were no nearby smokers.  The nausea was pretty severe. I felt like vomiting but never did. I did have some diarrhea.  This continued at its most severe through April 6. On that date, I called my doctor who recommended I use flonase. I had also started taking Tylenol Severe Sinus.  My symptoms improved after starting the meds. My doctor also recommended I get a Covid test. I got the rapid test on April 7. It was negative.  By April 9, my symptoms were mostly gone, including the smell of smoke. I also had side effects after the first vaccination on March 8. On March 9 and 10, I had a severe sinus headache.  On March 10 and 11, I was very nauseated and vomited twice. I also experienced fatigue for about 5 days.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I suffer from a genetic condition called Hereditary Angioedema.   Prior to preventative medicine (Tahkzyro) availability, I treated each attack acutely with Firazry/Icatibant.   My swelling attacks were rare (no more than 6 times per year, and one injection stopped the attacks.    When Tahkzyro was approved as a prevention (every two week injection), in Oct. 2018, I began to administer this medicine 2x per month.   This eliminated ALL attacks to my extremities, but not to my abdominal area.   Those attacks were reduced to 4/yr, with a recurrence of attack within a day of first attack.  Firazry/icatibant had to be injected again (after six hours) and within a day, the attack would stop.  Tracking my triggers, I found consistency in the following (all three situations would have to be present).   1. Near my menstruation cycle. 2. Some viral-like symptom (scratchy throat/allergy, virus/illness). 3. Some stressor (activity, emotional, or weather-related).   None of these things, alone, set off an attack.  They have to occur around the same time.  My Johnson and Johnson vaccine was administered on March 18.   My period was due on April 3.  My period is 95% on time, always.  Depending on the timeframe for PMS/horomones, I would say that the injection was proceeded by my body entering into this phase.   On Mary 21, I experience my first abdominal attack in 6-8 months.  I injected Icatibant and after 6 hours, had to inject again due to a recurring attack.  I ordered a refill on my injections.   On April 2, I travelled to for vacation.  On April 4, I experienced the first of several abdominal attacks.  I ran out of medicine and had to have a new order shipped to my hotel (this had never happened before).   My menstruation was also late.  By April 9, my menstruation arrived, with a flow extremely higher than I recalled ever having in my adult life.   My abdominal attacks also ceased by that point.  I believe that having received this vaccine (which I am told has some form of the virus), during my PMS stage, along with over exerting myself with activities, created the three situations that occur to create a very painful, debilitating, abdominal attack.

She got her vaccine and had a rapid rise in BP and pulse, and ended up in the UC.  From there she was sick and down for 8 days with body aches, prickly feeling all over her skin, just general fatigue and feeling sick.  At 7 days after the vaccine she started with some arrhythmia problems, and had acute anxiety.  Muscles/ribs very sore to touch.  Whole upper body is inflamed.  Those symptoms continued for 7 weeks, but the inflammation decreased in the muscles/joints diminished.   7 weeks after receiving the vaccine because of the acute inflammation and anxiety she ended up 3 nights and days with no sleep.  She went to the UC again and they gave her something for that.  She is still having heart arrhythmias as her heart is inflamed.  Then starting the 1st week in April she started getting sick.  The arrhythmias increased to palpitations to PVC's that began to increase.  She became dizzy, light headed at times, the nausea started, the palpitations were painful and then went to see a cardiologist.  He is trying to get medications to stop the palpitations.  So far they are waiting for the medication to take effect.  She has been down for 5 days, she is weak, dizzy when she is up.  Her BP and pulse are stable, EKG is normal.  She is also having what she is calling surges and/or storms, acute anxiety storms that rush through her body which makes her body feel like fire rushing through her body, acute panic.  It causes her to have to lie down and curl up, fatigue, dizziness and nausea to go with that.  It does subside slowly, but takes about 2 hours.  She has ongoing symptoms that are increasing in severity and are trying to treat the symptoms, but so far just waiting for things to work    She has never been sick, never had anxiety issues.  There is nothing in her environment that would cause these reactions.   She believes that the storms are being brought on by the storm surges that are coming and going.

Repeat EKG demonstrated ST elevation again, and he was started on ibuprofen 600 mg every 6 hours. Chest pain recurred in the evening of 4/11, but resolved some time after administration of ibuprofen. Troponin level upon arrival to Hospital were 3.92 at 17:11 on 4/11, then rose 8.68 at 23:42 on 4/11 at the time of his worsening chest pain. Chest pain still resolved by morning of 4/12, and troponin level downtrended to 5.87 at 6:22 on 4/12. Diagnosis consistent with myopericarditis.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This was the 2nd Moderna Shot on 2-18-2021.  She received the first shot on 1-22-2021. Patient verbally reported to me that about 4 hours after the shot, she began experiencing severe shocks all over her face and into her left neck and chest area.  This quickly worsened to include her left arm.  That all resolved after a nap.  But when she woke up, and went to the mirror, she noted that her left face was slow and drooping.  She went to the ER.  It was noted that she was having a severe problem with swallowing.  She also was noting severe pain in left external ear canal.  She had obvious severe breakout in the left ear canal - and the immediate area.  She was sent home - and came to my office the next day.  By that time, the symptoms had become much much worse.  She was unable to swallow.  The outbreak in the left ear was much more pronounced.  And her entire left face and left tongue were paralyzed.  She was diagnosed with the Ramsay-Hunt Syndrome - she was unable to talk or swallow.  She was readmitted back into the hospital.
LAB_DATA: An extensive 6 week hospital stay with feeding tubes and multiple diagnostic tests.  The main issue was pain control as she was in horrific unending pain the entire time.  Was unable to speak well and lost the ability to swallow.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Immediately after receiving his covid vaccine patient started feeling nauseaus/dizzy, and threw up. After throwing up he felt better.

About  4-5 hours after her first shot she started getting and itchy feeling.  This carried on for the next several weeks.  She felt like the itching feeling may have improved a little just a couple days prior to her second vaccine, but then the symptoms came back even worse after her second vaccination. She saw her primary care and was noted to be very jaundiced.  She was sent to the emergency department where her bilirubin was greater than 12.  She ultimately was admitted to the hospital.  She had no abdominal pain, nausea, or vomiting.   She had persistent elevation of her bilirubin.  Workup was done during the hospitalization including lab work, MRI of the liver, liver biopsy.  She was also found to have choledocholithiasis on the MRI.  ERCP was done with  stone extraction.   Bilirubin trended down several days later to around seven.  She followed up with me in the office where repeat lab work was unchanged.
LAB_DATA: Bili 12.2 on 3/10/2021 Bili 6.8 on 3/22/2021 MRCP - choledocholithiasis and cholecystitis ERCP 3/11/2021 - stones removed Liver biopsy 3/12/2021 - acute paricholangitis, portal fibrosis, early septal fibrosis stage 2.

After about 7 minutes of getting the Janssen Covid-19 vaccines, patient husband said patient is not feeling well.  I attended to patient immediately.  She said she is not feeling well, and her eye was rolling (as if when she tried to look up and couldn't get their eye to remain open) a for about few seconds and then she her eye was open back to normal.  She was sweating on both hands and face were cold to the touch.  I got the manager from the store to help me lie patient flat on the floor's surface gently to prevent her from falling off the chair.    Based on this our adverse event protocol, patient exhibited similar symptoms to Syncope (paleness, sweating, coldness of extremities), so I patient is lying flat on the floor, feet elevated, and cold compression was apply on her arms and face.  Unfortunately, patient conditions was not improving as it seem but she was alert and able to breath (fast pace) the whole entire time the incident occurred where she answer all questions when we myself, then the paramedics asked her questions.  Paramedic arrived at scene within 10 minutes after individual got off the phone with 911.  They took her away around 9 am and said patient probably experience anxiety attack.
CUR_ILL: Patient didn't specified, however, she told the paramedic personnel when they asked if she has anxiety attack before and she answered yes.  The paramedic personnel told me based on her symptoms (sweating, numbing on hands which lead to pain, and breathing fast), she probably have anxiety attacked.
HISTORY: Based on the profile we have for patient, no chronic health condition.  Patient didn't specified when she come to get the vaccine today.
ALLERGIES: Shell Fish: She have trouble breathing Robaxin: She swollen up but took when she was around 16 years old, so she can't recall if ther e is any breathing problem.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Tightness in throat, breathing problems, used my albuteral inhaler 2x, coughing, very itchy all within 10 minutes of the shot.  I was taken back to a separate room and seen by paramedics.
LAB_DATA: Paramedics at the shot site  put in an IV administered 50mg of benedryl.  Helped some, but I started getting worse with my breathing, it was decided that I needed to go to the hospital and receive further treatment.  In the ambulance I received decadran,  a nebulizer breathing treatment, then dropped off  at the hospital where I received Pepsi?s and was watched for an hour then released.  On day 2(4/11/21) symptoms were worsening, severe itching, and vascular bruising, which I was concerned it was blood clotting.  Went back to the ER(sky ridge hospital lone tree colorado) had another IV of benedryl, steroids, Pepcid, and determined that the bruising was not blood clots but some type of reaction to the vaccine.  Given prescriptions for prednisone, Pepcid, epi pen, benedryl, to keep the regimen going for 5 days.  Day 3 -  all symptoms still very prevalent, I am seriously considering going back to the emergency room.  Breathing is difficult, using a nebulizer and inhaler every 4 hours, benedryl (50mg) every 4 hour to try to manage the hives, itching.
OTHER_MEDS: Baclofen Lunesta Allegra Progesterone  Synthroid Liothronnine Topomax Pepsi?s Lexapro D3 Dexilant Crestor

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Initially, I felt fine. Several hours later I began to feel run down, like a cold. I then began to have an ache near my right kidney that I attributed to laying weirdly. However, I also began experiencing a sort of menstrual cramping on my right side as well. This has persisted since Friday night. Today (4/12/21) at about 02:30 pm, I got my period 10 days early! This isn't normal for me. Right now it is as if I'm spotting (dark discharge to warn that full-on bleeding will happen soon). I don't usually spot. My period is rather predictable and I have been dutiful in my tracking as my cycle has shortened over the years, going from a 28 day to 25 day cycle. The malaise and aches are consistent with my PMS, but I just wasn't expecting my period right now. I really don't understand how this is happening.
LAB_DATA: I don't know, but I'm open to exploring this phenomenon more.  https://www.health.com/condition/infectious-diseases/coronavirus/can-covid-vaccine-affect-my-period

SYMPTOM_TEXT: After one week of the injection I had a rash at the injection site and my lips became extremely irritated, raw and had a burning sensation. They started to swell and grew more irritate with every OTC topical lip treatment. After emailing my doctor she thought it was a form of skin infection and put me on Zyrtec and told me to stop treating the lips. My lips became more inflamed, the burning became more severe and the inflammation of my lips became so large that I could barely speak. I went to urgent care where the doctor told me it was a different form of skin infection and put me on antibiotics. He advised against a steroid shot but did give me one dose of oral steroids to take if condition worsened. Was told to apply vaseline only. Condition continued to worsen so I took the steroid dose in the morning and contacted my doctor. She worked with an allergist who told me it was yet another form of skin infection. The allergist told me to use toothpaste, take mints and gave me a topical steroid. The topical steroid immediately helped. I am on day four of antibiotics and topical steroids and am continuing to see relief.

client complained of nausea, tingling and numbness to both arms after receiving 1st dose of Pfizer. Client had been sitting on waiting room approximately 5 mins after vaccine when she alerted EMT she was feeling nauseous. EMT gave emesis bag to client and PHN joined shortly after. Per client has history of anxiety and felt an episode occurring. First vitals at 1100: blood pressure 150/100, pulse 75. Client stated nausea had resolved, but now was starting to feel numbness and tingling to both arms down to fingers. Client stated room felt claustrophobic. Walked client over to patio door for fresh air. Client alert and oriented, history of anxiety, type 2 diabetes and only medication she takes is Metformin. No known allergies. PHN assessed for sensory and motor on both arms. Client denied chest pain, numbness radiating anywhere past shoulders, or shortness or breath. 1105 per client fresh air was helping, could feel her anxiety was improving. 1108 vitals: blood pressure 130/90, pulse 82, oxygen 98%. Per client was feeling better, wanted to leave facility. Client advised be best to complete 30min observation. Client stated she was fine and wanted to leave, had someone waiting outside and would drive. ER precautions given. Client left facility with steady gait at 1110.

53 y.o. female with a PMhx of asthma, CHF, CKD (not on HD), DM, HTN, hypothyroidism, methadone dependence for back pain, chronic bilateral foot ulcers presents with c/o one day of fever and admitted for sepsis of unknown origin on 3/9. Patient tested negative for SARSCOV2 on admission on 3/9. She was deemed a candidate for the vaccine and it was administered on 3/10 (Janssen Lot 1805031).  On 3/19, she tested positive for SARSCOV2. She developed worsening respiratory failure and required oxygen supplementation with gradual escalation until she was intubated on 3/29. She received 5 days of remdesivir and steroid therapy. She developed DIC for which she received supportive care (vitamin K, transfusions, etc) and an HLH-type picture for which the steroids treatment was prolonged. She was not a candidate for tocilizumab given the elevated LFTs > 5x the upper limit of normal. During the ICU course patient was started on hemodialysis. Patient gradually started improving around 4/5 with planning for spontaneous breathing trials in attempts to extubate after weaning of sedatives. On 4/8, during a dialysis session patient became hypotensive and bradycardic. After this episode, patient's mental status worsened and developed worsening metabolic acidosis and worsening shock refractory to vasopressors. Family decided for DNR and transition to comfort care. Patient expired on 4/12.

RN placed pt's torso and head in her arms and moved patient to the floor into a supine position with legs raised onto his chair (pt did not fall to the ground). Once on the floor, pt opened eyes and asked RN, "Did I fall asleep?" RN reassure pt that he may have fainted while sitting in his chair. RN reassured pt and gave pt bottle water to drink. Color returning to patients face.   10:40: Pt reports "I'm feeling much better." Pt sitting upright  on the floor.   10:45: Pt sitting up in chair. Alert to person, place, and time. Color WNL, peripheral pulses strong. Pt reports feeling well enough to leave. RN encourage pt to stay a few minutes longer to make sure able to stand/walk to his car.  10:50: Pt left observation area.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: After being screened to enter the healthcare facility and completing the intake screening for COVID vaccine, patient received the Janssen COVID vaccine at approximately 11:00am.  Several minutes later while sitting in the observation area, patient stated that he felt like throwing up and that he had a headache.  He said he just started feeling tired.  He denied any shortness of breath, swelling in his mouth or throat, or rashes.  He stated he had not eaten breakfast in the morning.  When his vital signs were checked, his blood pressure was 149/94 and heart rate was 90.  He was alert and oriented.  He was transported to the facility urgent care for further assessment and observation. In urgent care, he appeared to become more lethargic, although his vital signs remained stable.  911 was called.   While waiting for the ambulance, staff spoke to the patient's brother (who had been waiting outside for patient).  Patient's brother stated that patient had a fever and stomachache the night before, and that patient had a recent surgery and had not completed his post-op antibiotic course.  Patient's brother stated that he came to clinic anyways for the vaccine appointment because he wanted to get the COVID vaccine so that he could return to work (as required by his employer).   Patient was transported to  Hospital.  Per nurse report, he was released from the emergency room after a brief observation period.
LAB_DATA: None at this facility (unsure if any tests were done at the emergency department where patient was transferred)
CUR_ILL: recent surgery (unknown reason/type of surgery or date of surgery) reported by patient's brother

Patient suffered cardiac arrest during his transportation to the emergency room.  A CPR was initiated and was given 3 rounds of epinephrine.  Most of the history is taken from the ER physician chart review.   ACUTE RESPIRATORY FAILURE SECONDARY TO HYPOXEMIA, COVID-19 , cardiac arrest, possible anoxic brain damage  : Patient is 62-year-old male with complicated history with history of hepatitis-C, cirrhosis, alcohol use, cocaine abuse diabetes who presented after having cardiac arrest and possible anoxic brain damage.  Patient was intubated after the arrest.  Patient stayed in the hospital for number of days.  Patient was found to have COVID-19 positive.  Patient was found to have diffuse bilateral infiltrate.  Patient was started on broad-spectrum antibiotics including cefepime Flagyl and Decadron.  Due to patient's cardiac arrest patient was started on hypothermia protocol.  Patient was rewarming after that.  There was no purposeful movement or neurological recovery.  After long discussion with the family, patient has been made comfort care.  Patient was extubated.  Patient expired promptly after that.  Family is notified.

The patient received his 2nd dose of Moderna (LOT#, site, time unavailable) at an outside clinic the morning of 2/10/21 and presented to the ED with coughing and hypoxia (sp02 occasionally dropping into 70's) at 8 PM that day.  He had quadriplegic spinal paralysis as a result of a remote MVA and has been hospitalized and critically ill in the past due to recurrent UTI's and pneumonia with associated sepsis.   CT negative for pulmonary embolism and showed bilateral infiltrates.  Clinical presentation consistent with bilateral pneumonia and started on Rocephin/azithromycin.  He was initially stable in the hospital on 1-2 LPM 02.  The following evening he became febrile and acutely developed asystole without any pre-existing arrhythmia.  Resuscitation was attempted for 45 minutes but unsuccessful.  Overall, I suspect his death was related to bacterial pneumonia and resulting acute respiratory failure, complicated by his quadriplegia and autonomic dysreflexia but reported this event as it did occur within 2 days of receiving his 2nd Moderna vaccination.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Within a few hours of receiving my first COVID Moderna vaccine on 2/12/21, I became very sick with a fever around 101 and severe muscle aches. Overnight, I woke up with numbness down the whole left side of my body and I was unable to move my left leg for several minutes. The pain from the injection site radiated from my right arm to my neck, back, shoulders, and to my fingertips. The next day I continued to feel very sick especially with moderate/severe joint pain. I then completed my second dose of the vaccine on 3/29/21. Again within hours I became very sick, and by around midnight I was crying in pain from the severe joint pain. It felt like shooting pains down both arms and both legs that went on constantly for about two miserable days. I could hardly eat or drink anything and was vomiting, having chills/fever, headache, fatigue, nausea, etc. I would describe the experience as moderate to severe symptoms as I was close to going to the hospital but knew I couldn't even drive myself in that state. It was definitely sicker than I have ever been from the cold, flu, or any other illness. I am a 28 year old healthy and physically fit female aside from this experience. For both shots, it took about 48 hours to recover. Once I had a fever both times (within hours) I began taking Tylenol which only slightly took the edge off but still did not make me comfortable or able to go to work.

Janssen COVID-19 Vaccine:  Vaccine administered by pharmacy staff at 1320, patient was observed for 15 minutes without complaint or concern.  Upon check-out he stated he was "starting to feel sweaty".  He denied dizziness, difficulty breathing, chest pain or other concerns.  Systolic blood pressure was 76/40 (manual), heart rate 70.  He remained awake, alert, skin pale,  clammy,  & cool.  Sweat noted on forehead, in no acute distress.  He was transferred to supine position and given cold water.  BP increased to 124/82, heart rate 88, pulse ox 98%.  He verbalized he felt much better, stated he began to have concerns about a reaction when he began to feel sweaty.  He was unsure if it was anxiety or a reaction to the vaccine as the feelings began to escalate.  He has no history of similar reactions but "doesn't like shots".    He has no medical history, takes no medications/supplements and is otherwise "healthy".  He ate lunch prior to appointment.  Additional BP readings remained within normal limits,  skin warm/dry, back to baseline.  Observed for an additional 45 minutes and returned to work.  Discharge vitals: 116/84, 90, 98%, 16.

The patient developed a sore arm in the arm that received the vaccination,  as could be expected,  in the early morning the day following her injection. The symptoms progressed to include a knot at the injection site with intensifying pain in the area. By day 8, she had lost mobility in the affected arm to the point of not being able to lift the arm or perform regular daily activities. When visiting the pharmacy seven weeks after the injection, she asked to talk me concerning her adverse reactions. I questioned her about where the injection was given by the vaccinator and confirmed that it was given in the center area of the left deltoid muscle. I suggested that I felt like she was coincidentally having symptoms from a shoulder injury.  She saw her primary care provider  who suggested she alternate cold and heat to the area with no relief. She then saw an orthopedist on 4/8/21 who performed an exam and performed an X-ray. He told the patient that there had been severe bruising and bleeding in the muscle that had developed a calcification. He referred her back to her primary care provider for further treatment.  After discussing this finding  with the patient, I surmised that the unusual amount of injury and bleeding to the area was due to her taking Eliquis 5 mg  twice daily.

Began having the sensation of being poked with needles all over my body.   Continuously.   Like a severe tingling.   Head to toe, including face and extremities.  ( With the 1st dose, I had the same sensations on a very slight level, and only on arms and legs and not all the time).    Sensations started day 2.  Severe at day 4, when I had to drive 4 hours to another State.  Accompanied by random dizziness, and feeling mentally "out of it" a little.  I'd read it was Ok to exercise after getting the shots, so Day 2 and 3 I attempted crossfit.   I got thru the classes, barely.    Afterward I thought I was going to pass out and I felt bizarre, mostly my head.    Very unwell.   I would also get random hot flashes with dizziness.   I am perimenopause, but dont have hot flashes very much any longer and they dont make me dizzy.    With the day 4 severity of the needles sensation,  I honestly started to worry.   I decided Id see a doctor upon my return to home, which would be day 7.    Today is day 7 after dose 2.   Huge improvement, but still having some of the sensations,  so I dont plan to reach out to my doctor unless my next workout feels like the ones last week.   I expected the common side effect of tiredness and fever chills, but got this crazy stuff that felt like my nervous system was misfiring/freaking out.   I am afraid to get a booster shot for Covid if that's the path in a few months!

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient was previously healthy and got her second injection in the right arm on 1/25/2021.  She had severe weakness of the right arm starting the day after the immunization, headaches across the whole head, severe fatigue, confusion (brain fog), worsening depression, body aches, and these all progressed and got worse for at least 14 days.  She was unable to work any of those days due to weakness, confusion, and body aches.  She saw me in the clinic on March 2 as she was still feeling weak, tired, confused.  The clinic notes that day record:  "On the next day, the 26th, she had severe pain and couldn't do much. Then she got super depressed and could not get out of bed for 2 weeks, had a lot of fatigue, body aches, and felt down. She tried going to the store one day and by the time she got done she could not get into her truck because she was in so much pain. That would have been about 2 weeks ago. She went back to work last week and was at work the whole week. She was told she does have leave time and that it did not cover the absence of work. She now needs new leave time forms completed.  Currently she is in a lot of pain. She has her endocrine appointment on March 15th. The pain is getting worse. The cold is really hard on her. She is barely able to move her right arm at the end of the day, and that is the arm where she had the COVID shot. She is having a lot more weakness. She can not even take one flight of stairs now because everything hurts her. This is a huge difference than before. She used to be able to do several flights, and she can't do that anymore.  She has also had vision changes. She has floaters but she is having a harder time focusing. She feels like no one would believe her, but she feels like this is all part of the reaction to COVID. She has a hard time focusing. She feels like she is going insane."

SYMPTOM_TEXT: He tested positive for COVID-19 on April 7 2021.  He qualified for monoclonal antibody therapy and presented for that therapy 4/9/2021.  After starting the infusion he developed sudden onset shortness of breath.  He is noted to be wheezing.  He was given Solu-Medrol and benadryl prior to transfer to ED.   Acute hypoxic respiratory failure in patient with recent Covid diagnosis with sudden worsening during monoclonal antibody infusion.  Differential includes allergic reaction/anaphylaxis, flash pulmonary edema, worsening Covid. Given the wheezing he was given a DuoNeb with no significant improvement but may be slightly decreased wheezing.  Patient was placed on BiPAP given concern for pulmonary edema and increased work of breathing.  We were able to titrate down the FiO2 to 40%.  He was transitioned to high flow nasal cannula.  Will admit to the hospital for further supportive cares given Covid and hypoxic respiratory failure.

CONTRAST: IOHEXOL 350 MG IODINE/ML IV 75 ML: 75mL   FINDINGS: ANGIOGRAM CHEST: No pulmonary artery filling defects. The aorta is normal in caliber. Partially visualized simple or benign left renal cyst is again seen. No dedicated follow-up is required.   MUSCULOSKELETAL: Degenerative changes of the spine.   IMPRESSION: 1.  No pulmonary embolus. 2.  COVID pneumonia. There may be a component of superimposed pulmonary edema. 3.  A few mildly enlarged mediastinal lymph nodes are favored to be reactive. 4.  Mild cardiomegaly. 5.  Hepatic steatosis.

2 Events: Evening following 2nd injection, I went from having no dental issues to having severe tooth pain on lower left jaw, roughly 4-5 teeth in from back molar.  Swelling began within hours accompanied by intense pain and sensitivity.  By that Sunday evening, swelling had extended up to left eye, over to bottom of ear, and down neck to baseline and half way to center jaw line.  Bruising present.  Throbbing was constant.  Made emergency dental appointment for Monday, but by that Sunday night, I could not stand it any longer and was afraid the swelling would extend to my throat.  Went to ER, who diagnosed an abcess under the tooth root.  Perscribed pain pills and antibiotics.  Saw dentist Monday, who scheduled me for an emergency root canal on Tuesday.  Got root canal on a tooth I never had problems with before, although there certainly could have been an issue brewing but not yet pronounced.  Anyway, he also drained what he called an unbelievable amount of infection fluid (pus) after making an incision in my gum line and basically squeezing my face to get as much out as he could.  Said he never saw anything like it.  And for me to go from 0 to that in a matter of days was incredible.  I thought perhaps it was an immune response?  At the same time that I was experiencing the dental issue, I started to develop a strong dry cough.  I have a light former smokers cough, and have had pneumonia many times, but this cough was different.  Every day it has gotten strongly, but is very much intermittent.  I now go into fits of coughing that last one to two minutes and so strong and to the point where I have either fractured my rib directly beneath my right breast, or something else is going on.  These fits can last minutes, but never result in expulsion of phlegm.  The coughing fits also occur if I take a deeper breath, walk too far, laugh, or talk too long.  Very strange.  I am very fatigued and have been since the onset of the dental issue reported above.    While the dental issue is gone since the absess was drained, the cough is still present, and wakes me up every single night too with coughing fits.  The cough has loosened up a bit.  I would go to the doctor, but I am in the middle of a move from MO to AZ, and just arrived in AZ after a 3 day drive.  So, first off, I am reporting this issue.  And next, I will seek a new doctor in Arizona if this cough continues.
LAB_DATA: Root canal 3/30 -  just xrays that showed the infection under the root

HISTORY: Bronchitis/Pre-COPD High Blood Pressure and Chlorestoral Overweight Depression

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Janssen COVID-19 Vaccine  During the injection I had extreme pain in my left arm at the injection site.  This lasted for about 1 hour and then calmed down to a dull ache.    About 7 pm Wednesday night (April 7) I started a low grade fever of 99.6 degrees.  Over the next three hours it increased to 102 degrees.  It stayed this high for about five hours.  (During this time I also experienced severe, almost uncontrollable shivering.)  Then it slowly dropped back down to 100 degrees by about 5 am.  It remained there for about 12 hours.  Then at about 5 pm it dropped to about 99.6 degrees where it stayed until I went to bed at 10 pm.  When I woke up at 2:30 am Friday morning I was covered in sweat and the fever was gone.    In addition to the fever, I had a moderate to severe headache, extreme body aches and Joint pain, as well as exhaustion.  As the fever diminished, these symptoms did as well.    By Friday afternoon all I had was some body aches and joint pain along with a minor headache.    By Saturday I was fully recovered other than some minor discomfort at the injection site.

On the evening of Friday 4/2/2021 around 9:30 PM, I was experiencing what felt like heartburn. It got better before I went to bed. At around 9:00 AM on Saturday 4/3/2021, I was awakened by intense pain and pressure that felt like the worst heartburn I'd ever experienced. After OTC heartburn treatments didn't help, at around 11:00 AM I went to the local ER where I was initially diagnosed as having a heart attack. After being given some baby aspirin and a nitro tablet, I started feeling better and was airlifted immediately to a nearby cardiology unit at another hospital. A heart catheterization and EKGs determined that I had not had a heart attack, but instead had takotsubo cardiomyopathy. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Had a sore arm within hour of shot (got it at 7:30pm). Felt a little yucky before going to bed. I made sure to hydrate significantly before the shot and after. Mild ache in joints and body overall. At 10am I took one ibuprofen, but at 11am (200mg), kept pushing fluids. 11am headache got worse temp 98.7 (slightly high for me, I am usually about 97). Started having some gastrointestinal issues around noon. Felt nausea and sweaty palms loss of appetite. Had a bowel movement (normal in appearance).    That all seemed to pass and I felt better, still tired, for most of the afternoon. Arm was sore to the touch and when moving. I managed to eat a few small meals, kept up hydration, and took a nap late in the day. I woke up at 5pm with headache and body aches all over. No appetite again. Had very little to eat, kept hydrating,    At 7pm my vision got a little blurry and I had a minor vasovagal episode. Center of vision blurred, got chills and sweaty, nausea, and I had to poop  (it was less formed). I rested, cool compress, and raised my feet. It all passed in about 20 minutes. I had major loss of appetite rest of the night (couldn't eat anything), kept hydrating, and went to bed.  Slept through the night with no incidents.   Woke up at 9am second day and had a small breakfast, though my appetite is still not back. Generally feeling exhausted, but no headache or aches in the body anymore. My arm is still sore. Had some more GI distress (another less formed poop around 11am).   My appetite returned by early afternoon on the 2nd day post-vaccine. Still tired and generally feeling "off," especially mentally. Had brain fog all afternoon and my ears felt plugged today. Hard to concentrate on a task.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received the J&J one-dose vaccine on Thursday, April 8, at approx. 1600. Within an hour I had a mild headache and was nauseous. I went to sleep around 2130. At 0030 (or 30 minutes past midnight) I was awoken to the sudden shock of feeling very cold. My temperature was 91, within 15 minutes I spiked to 100 degrees, and then 15 minutes later I was at 102. I was shivering but felt like I was on fire. I had intense pain throughout my entire body. Internally and topically (skin) my entire body felt like it was on fire -- a burning sensation. Clothes -- even a soft hoodie -- felt like a steel wool scrubber was brushing against my skin and my skin was very hot to touch. I continued to feel nauseous.  After 90 minutes of this, I was able to take acetaminophen (2 x 500 mg). After another 90 minutes, my temperature dipped to 99 and the horrible pain mostly subsided.   From 0530 to 1830, in three-hour increments, my temperature continued to spike and fall between 99-101 degrees and the pain came in the same waves. Nausea continued. So, I continued an acetaminophen regimen throughout the day to help with the symptoms and took a few tums to help too.  After 1830, I felt very weak and tired. My temperature stabilized at normal. Nausea continued.   On Saturday, April 10, I was mostly just tired and had minor body aches/soreness. My shoulder bruised where I was vaccinated. Food did not sit well and my stomach was quick to turn.   Sunday, April 11, mostly back to normal. Although, still fatigued. No major side effects or symptoms.   Monday, April 12, seems to be the same as Sunday.   Note: I had COVID the first week of February 2021.

ALL my lymph glands/nodes are quite swollen throughout my body!! Temp of 100.4 at its highest yesterday (Sunday, April 11th)! I have not had my spleen enlarge since the 1990's!

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 4/8/21:  I receive the injection at 1:50pm on my left arm.  8pm: I begin experiencing normal side effects: soreness, body aches, and headache.  9pm: In addition to the soreness, body aches, and headache, I start having chills, which last on and off throughout the night. 4/9/21:  7am: I feel fatigued, with headache and body aches throughout the morning and afternoon. 3pm: I begin to have some itchiness on my forehead and both ears. My right knee cap feels hot and bruised, but there is no mark. 5pm: Visible hives appear on my forehead and right knee cap, and my ears are red. All of these spots are very itchy and uncomfortable.  9pm: The hives begin to be much more noticeable and itchier. I take one Benadryl before going to bed which helps the itchiness somewhat. 4/10/21  3:30am: I am woken up by pain in my ears and they have gotten incredible swollen, red, and hot. They are very tender to the touch. I take another tablet of Benadryl.  7am: There are more hives on my forehead and cheeks, as well as my knee and now on two of my fingers. A few spots also appear on my feet and on one toe. My ears are less swollen but still not back to normal, and they are still red, hot and tender.  9am: I have a video call with a Physician?s Assistant who determines it is most likely not an anaphylactic reaction (no swelling in my throat or eyes or any of the other red flag symptoms. I also take my blood pressure with a home monitor and it is normal). He prescribes me a steroid pack.  12pm: The hives begin to be less and less itchy and red.  8pm: The hives are almost completely gone, save for a few spots on my feet. As I am breastfeeding my 14-month-old daughter, I had waited to begin the steroid pack until after our last nursing session of the day (around 7:30pm). As the hives seemed to be going away on their own, I decide to not take the medication. I do take one dose of Zyrtec. 4/11/21:  7am: the hives are completely gone
HISTORY: History of Nontraumatic cortical hemorrhage of left cerebral hemisphere, Cerebral Venous Thrombosis and Stroke (January 2018)

Patient received her second Pfizer covid vaccine on Tuesday 4/6/21. She said she had been doing yard work before she came to get her vaccine. After she received her vaccine she felt fine. On Tuesday night she started to feel some itchiness. She said the itchiness got worse over the next two days. She talked to her husband and he advised her to take Benadryl so she took two Benadryl. On Wednesday she had some soreness at her injection site. Very early Thursday morning she noticed a golf ball sized knot in her armpit. She said it was sore and if she rubbed it, it felt like it was pushing into her breast. She said it felt like pressure going all the way to her breast bone and along her esophagus. She ended up calling EMS and her blood pressure was up to 181/107 and had a high heart rate. She said she never had any hives but did have some throat, tongue, and lip swelling and said that her throat felt raw. The EMS gave her 2 nitroglycerin tablets and 5 aspirin. She spent Friday and Saturday in the hospital. She said the hospital did all kinds of cardiac tests on her and everything can back clear besides a leaky heart valve. She said she is feeling much better now and that the hospital was not sure if it was a reaction to the vaccine, something else, or a combination of things that caused it.
OTHER_MEDS: Diltiazem 24H ER (CD) 12mg  Hydrocodone-Acetaminophen 5-325mg  Alprazolam 1mg Latanoprost 0.005% eye drops

Received a call 1650 c/o tongue swollen and feeling like it has "pins and needles". Denies any difficulty breathing. Able to speak clearly without any audible signs of distress.  Received dose of vaccine at 1600 today.  Originally called our call center who instructed her to call 911.She refused stating she just wanted to take Benadryl. Call transferred to me.  Instructed that per our Emergency medical orders, Benadryl is for urticaria, not for swelling of airway.  Instructed to call 911. She declined stating she wanted to try Benadryl first. Explained that a blocked airway can happen fast and she doesn't want to risk waiting too long.  Epi is recommended. She states she has a severe allergy to bees (which she did not list on the registration form--so only had a 15 minute wait versus 30 after her injection)--She states she has 6 epi pens readily available with her.  Confirms she has someone there with her. Instructed that my recommendation would be to call 911, but if she isn't going to do that she needs to have her epi pens ready and available and ensure that the person she is with knows how to use them. If she develops any trouble breathing, they need to give epi and call 911, then repeat dose every 5-10 minutes until paramedics arrive. She agrees with that plan.  Agrees to have another nurse call her later to f/u.  Called again several times that evening by RN--at 1735 she was advised to use her epi pen and call 911, she declined. She finally had boyfriend drive her to ER to "sit in parking lot" in case something got worse. enc to have boyfriend go into ER and alert them. RN also called ER to give them an alert.  Continued to decline to use Epi pen.  Declined to let RN speak to boyfriend either.  Rn tried to call her later and she didn't answer.  RN left a message, but she didn't call back.
LAB_DATA: Called her back after the fact--she stated she did go to the ER Parking lot and sat there with her boyfriend. Never developed trouble breathing so never went into the ER.  She continued to take Benadryl which would help a little for a while for several days and her tongue stayed swollen for several days, Then it resolved and she if fine now. She never saw a medical provider and never used her epi pen.

Within a few minutes of receiving the vaccination I lost consciousness. It was a drive-through vaccination clinic by the Health department. My vehicle rolled into a cement and metal bar/side of the building's exit at a slow speed. The EMS at the scene stated that my heartbeat was irregular, varying between bradycardia and tachycardia. When they checked my blood pressure inside the ambulance they stated it was very low. About 15-20 minutes later I tried to sit up and was still unstable and unable to keep myself upright without assistance. I was then taken by ambulance to the nearest hospital's emergency department. Nothing notable or unusual was found when I was checked out there. Within a couple hours I felt well enough to go home. Once home I had a headache, fatigue, mild dizziness, and nausea with physical activity. The following day I had a headache, muscle aches, pain at the injection site, and nausea with extended physical activity. Today I have pain in the arm where I received the vaccine and a mild headache.
LAB_DATA: At the hospital on the day of the reaction (4/10/21), my CBC, CHEM7, and EKG results came back normal. My Covid test came back negative.

My father was given his second dose of the Pfizer vaccine on Feb. 13, 2021.  He went downhill the following week.  He fell 9 times and was very confused.  He was taken to the hospital on Feb. 20 and admitted that day.  He spent a week there.  His condition continued to deteriorate.  He was totally bedridden for a week.  His mental status deteriorated.  By Feb. 22, he was unable to talk, he drooled, and had to be fed.  He made  slow improvement later in the week.  We were never given any reason for his condition.  There was no infection, no stroke, etc.  He was discharged and sent to rehab on Feb. 27.  He remained there until April 8.   He is currently doing fairly well.  He uses a walker and gait belt in the house and is receiving home therapy.  He is not as independent as he was before.  His short term memory seems to be more impaired than it was previously.
LAB_DATA: Many tests were performed while he was a patient at the Hospital.

He kept stating he did not feel well. We advised him we call EMS and they are on the way.

Sudden sensorineural hearing loss (SSNHL) in left ear, beginning 8-9 days after vaccine on  March 19th Friday.   Symptoms of fullness, muffled hearing, sensitivity to sound.  This was coupled with increased/exacerbated tinnitus in both left and right ears.  Hearing test and physical exam done by ENT on March 22 Monday showed a loss of hearing in low frequencies in left ear of up to 40 DB.   Treatment with steroids was initiated (prednisone 50 mg for 7 days, 30 mg 1 day, 25 mg 1 day).   Follow-up visit to ENT on March 31 showed improvement in hearing nearly back to levels prior to the SSNHL; however tinnitus remained elevated.  Prednisone was continued at 40 mg for 1 week with taper.
LAB_DATA: Hearing test and physical exam done by ENT on March 22 Monday showed a loss of hearing in low frequencies in left ear of up to 40 DB.   Treatment with steroids was initiated (prednisone 50 mg for 7 days, 30 mg 1 day, 25 mg 1 day). SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt was administered the vaccine approximately 10:30 am. She reported feeling fine immediately after receiving the vaccine. She was carried to a chair and was able to sit upright on her own. She was able to speak in full complete sentences. She was alert and somewhat oriented. She said she felt very hot and dizzy. Her blood pressure @10:50 am was 108/81, pulse: 62, respiratory rate: 20. Vitals determined within safe limits. Pharmacy provided the patient with some water and Gatorade. We had the patient remain in sitting position. Patient reported slowly feeling better over time. Repeated vitals check @11:10 am with no significant change in blood pressure, pulse, and respiration.  Patient remained seated and when she was feeling better, attempted to call friends and family to come pick her up from the store. After approximately 1 hour after the event, patient was back to baseline. She was able to leave on her own without assistance.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient has long standing COPD and asthma. He has been stable on his home medications for years. No hospitalizations for these issues in the past. During Covid times he has been very restricted to his home with no visitors. Approximately 5 days after receiving the 2nd Moderna Covid-19 vaccine, he started having increased difficulty with breathing. Over the next few weeks he continued to get worse and required home oxygen and an adjustment with his medications. He was started on steroids and antibiotics about 3 weeks after the vaccine and then hospitalized on 3/16/2021 with COPD exacerbation and pneumonia. He tested negative for Covid at that time. He was in the hospital for 9 days and discharged home on steroid taper and home oxygen. A few days after being at home, he had gradual onset of subacute dementia/delirium. All workup has been negative. MRI/MRA normal. He is currently continuing on oxygen and again on steroids and mental status may be starting to improve.     The concern here is that patient was stable and had been stable on his medication regimen for years. He was doing well until approx 5 days after his second Covid vaccine when he started having worsening pulmonary complaints and eventually ended up in the hospital. He continues to be on oxygen at home and was recently started back on steroids. There has been no explanation for his subacute onset of Dementia/Delirium. MRI/MRA normal. This has been discussed with both Pulmonology and Neurology specialists.

My last period prior to my first vaccine shot had been in June 2020.  All signs, including blood work, pointed to me having entered menopause.  My mom also went through menopause at age 45 when her periods suddenly stopped, so I figured I was following in her footsteps.  On Saturday, February 13, 2021, I received my first dose of the Moderna vaccine, and by Thursday morning, I was spotting.  This was very surprising since I had not had a period in several months.  Over the course of a couple of days, it turned into a full-blown period with the most severe cramping I've ever had in my life.  By Saturday, they felt like labor contractions, and I was releasing sizable blood clots.  I made an appointment at our health clinic, and all bloodwork again pointed to menopause.  After my 2nd Moderna vaccine, I again experienced just a tiny bit of brown spotting a few days after the vaccine.  However, it did not progress into a full-blown period that time.
